1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:05,000
Welcome to this demonstration of Tetris in Ada, showcasing the DEGAS replacement runtime for regression testing.

2
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:10,000
While dtetris provides an interactive experience, ttetris is specifically designed for automated testing.

3
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:15,000
We start with ttetris running under the standard Ada runtime. Notice the slow, real-time progression.

4
00:00:15,500 --> 00:00:20,000
The game relies on wall-clock time for task scheduling and delays, which can be inefficient for testing.

5
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:25,000
Now, we switch to the DEGAS runtime. DEGAS enables high-speed testing by replacing wall-clock time with simulated time.

6
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:30,000
By intercepting pthread calls via LD_PRELOAD, DEGAS eliminates real-world waiting from Ada delay calls.

7
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:35,000
The result is instantaneous evaluation. This allows us to run complex test suites in a fraction of the time.

8
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:40,000
Beyond speed, DEGAS provides a deterministic and reproducible event order, ensuring that test results remain consistent.

9
00:00:40,500 --> 00:00:45,000
Finally, we see ttetris running again without DEGAS. Observe the non-determinism as the results differ each time.

10
00:00:45,500 --> 00:00:50,000
This variability makes regression testing unreliable. With DEGAS, we gain both speed and total reproducibility.
